abstract = {Background: The aerosol generated by an ultrasonic scaler contains micro-organisms that can penetrate into the body through the respiratory system of dental surgeons and patients. The aim of this pilot study was to evaluate and compare the efficacy of commercially available pre-procedural mouthrinses containing 0.2 \% chlorhexidine gluconate, a herbal mouthwash and water in reducing the levels of viable bacteria in aerosols. Methods: This was a single-center, double-masked, placebo-controlled, randomized, three-group parallel design and conducted over a period of 45 days. 24 patients with chronic periodontitis were divided randomly into three groups (A,B,C) of 8 patients each to be administered with 0.2 \% chlorhexidine gluconate, herbal mouthwash and water respectively, as a pre-procedural rinse. The aerosol produced by the ultrasonic unit was collected at patient's chest area, doctor's chest area and assistant's chest area on blood agar plates in all the three groups. The blood agar plates were incubated at 37o Celsius for 48 hours and the total number of colony- forming units (CFU) were counted and statistically analyzed. Results: The results showed that CFU in group A and group B were significantly reduced when compared to group C with P-value = 0.000 (ANOVA). Also, CFU in group A was significantly reduced when compared to group B with P-value < 0.05 (Independent t-test). The numbers of CFU were highest at patient's chest area and least on assistant's chest area. Conclusion: This study suggests that a routine pre-procedural mouthrinse could eliminate the majority of bacterial aerosols generated by the use of ultrasonic unit and 0.2\% chlorhexidine gluconate was more effective than herbal mouthwash.},
